---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { PageHeader } from '../app/components/ui/PageHeader';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Research | Ratish Gupta"
  description="Active work — a compute-in-memory transformer accelerator on FPGA, the SSCS PICO Chipathon, and notes from ISSCC 2026."
>
  <PageHeader
    client:load
    kicker="Research"
    title="Interests & Active Work"
    lede="Where my attention is right now: what I'm building, what I'm reading toward, and the questions I want to take into graduate research."
    back={{ to: '/', label: 'Back to Home' }}
  />
  <section class="max-w-[1200px] mx-auto px-6 md:px-12 lg:px-16 pb-24 md:pb-40">
    <div class="max-w-[68ch] flex flex-col gap-20">
      <div>
        <h2 class="font-sans text-[22px] text-[#ebe6dd] tracking-[-0.01em] pb-4 mb-8 border-b border-white/[0.08]">Active work</h2>
        <ul class="flex flex-col gap-7 font-serif text-[16px] text-[#a8a39a] leading-[1.75]">
          <li><span class="font-sans text-[#ebe6dd] font-medium tracking-[-0.005em]">Compute-in-memory transformer accelerator.</span> Self-directed capstone on FPGA, sequenced as seven milestones. M1 — an 8×8 INT8 output-stationary systolic MAC array — is verified bit-exact against a NumPy reference and closes timing at 100 MHz on Xilinx Artix-7. Subsequent milestones extend toward a full transformer datapath with attention and FFN blocks.</li>
          <li><span class="font-sans text-[#ebe6dd] font-medium tracking-[-0.005em]">SSCS PICO Chipathon.</span> Currently participating, aiming to build and submit a digital compute-in-memory design. Strong submissions earn the opportunity to publish through the IEEE Solid-State Circuits Society as an open-source design.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="font-sans text-[22px] text-[#ebe6dd] tracking-[-0.01em] pb-4 mb-8 border-b border-white/[0.08]">Conferences</h2>
        <ul class="flex flex-col gap-7 font-serif text-[16px] text-[#a8a39a] leading-[1.75]">
          <li><span class="font-sans text-[#ebe6dd] font-medium tracking-[-0.005em]">IEEE ISSCC 2026 — San Francisco.</span> Attended in person. Spent most of my time in the AI-accelerator and compute-in-memory sessions, and had conversations with engineers from Qualcomm, IBM, Samsung, Synopsys, and GSMC. The biggest takeaway: a large share of published work is bottlenecked by analog periphery and on-chip memory, not the compute fabric itself.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="font-sans text-[22px] text-[#ebe6dd] tracking-[-0.01em] pb-4 mb-8 border-b border-white/[0.08]">Heading toward</h2>
        <p class="font-serif text-[16px] text-[#a8a39a] leading-[1.75]">Graduate research in <span class="font-sans text-[#ebe6dd] font-medium tracking-[-0.005em]">ML-accelerator microarchitecture</span> — the boundary between algorithm intent, dataflow design, and the physical constraints of silicon. Specific questions I want to pursue:</p>
        <ul class="flex flex-col gap-4 font-serif text-[16px] text-[#a8a39a] leading-[1.75] mt-6 list-disc pl-6 marker:text-[#7a766e]">
          <li>Quantization-aware datapaths with sparsity-aware dispatch, and the architectural cost of supporting both dense and sparse workloads on the same fabric.</li>
          <li>Compute-in-memory beyond the demo — how the periphery (drivers, ADCs, accumulators) actually limits realistic workloads.</li>
          <li>Memory hierarchies for accelerators — bank-conflict avoidance, and the scratchpad-vs-coherent-cache trade-off for systolic and dataflow engines.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="font-sans text-[22px] text-[#ebe6dd] tracking-[-0.01em] pb-4 mb-8 border-b border-white/[0.08]">Reading</h2>
        <ol class="flex flex-col gap-8 list-decimal pl-6 marker:font-mono marker:text-[#7a766e] marker:text-[12px]">
          <li class="pl-2">
            <p class="font-serif text-[16px] text-[#cfc9bf] leading-[1.7]">
              <span class="text-[#ebe6dd]">Spear, C. &amp; Tumbush, G.</span>
              <em class="text-[#ebe6dd]">SystemVerilog for Verification</em>.
              <span class="text-[#8a8680]">Springer, 3rd ed., 2012.</span>
            </p>
            <p class="font-serif text-[14px] text-[#9a958c] italic leading-[1.7] mt-2">Most of my verification flow is cocotb in Python — this is the SystemVerilog-side context I'm filling in. SVA, randomization, coverage, and the constructs that don't naturally show up through a Python harness.</p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
